column49: NOTES

Greem Bell is the northernmost airfield in the world that regularly handles jet aircraft.  It operates under the authority of OGA (Arctic Control Group).  It appears to have been constructed in the late 1950s to guard the north approaches to Novaya Zemlya against reconnaissance flights, or as a front-line interceptor base for incoming American bombers.  Four Tu-128 long-range interceptors belonging to 72 GV AP (from Amderma) were based here in 1979.

North Pole-6 was opened April 1956 at 74 27'N 177 04'E to create a bomber staging airfield on a very large ice floe measuring 15 x 20 km and 15 m thick.  It was serviced by Tu-4, Il-12, Li-2, An-2, and Mi-4 from Tiksi.  By April 1957 it had drifted to 75 37'N 171 04'E.  A Tu-16A was lost during landing and abandoned 26 April 1958.  In April 1958 SP-6 was at 80 56'N 150 15'E.  Tu-4 aircraft continued to land in April 1959.  In April 1959 SP-6 was at 87 18'N 39 37'E.  Position given here is as of 1958 at time of the Tu-16 crash.  Research was done here as part of IGY (International Geophysics Year).  The site closed September 14, 1959, at which time the site position was 82 06'N 3 56'E.

This airfield operates under OGA (Arctic Control Group).  It is an extremely remote arctic base in the western Franz Josef Islands, located 820 km W of Sredniy airfield.  It was built in the 1950s as a staging base for Soviet bombers to reach the U.S.  An An-72 cargo plane crashed here 23 Dec 1996 while attempting to land, perhaps one of the northernmost plane crashes ever.  Services Mi-8, Mi-26, An-72, and An-26 aircraft.

This military airfield is under control of OGA (Arctic Control Group).  It is located in extreme northern Siberia close to the mainland.  It is an ice airfield that was probably intended as an alternate field for Tu-95 bombers in the Arctic.  It was built in late 1950s as a staging base for Soviet bombers to reach the U.S.

Ostrov Bolshevik was probably constructed around 1960, and due to the runway dimensions is believed to be a planned interceptor airfield covering a remote part of the Soviet Arctic which was abandoned during construction or served limited use. It may have been abandoned during the mid-1960s as the US bomber threat was eclipsed by ICBMs.
Tempa is a small utility airfield.  Its position is uncertain; a 1997 chart gives a position of 75-46N 137-36E in an alluvial fan; coarse satellite imagery shows a runway-like island in this area.

Dikson is a major airport that services small transport aircraft.  It is located on a small island across from the town of Dikson.  Central Intelligence Agency reports from 1952 released under the Freedom of Information Act indicate that the USSR was using Dikson as a staging airfield for Tupolev Tu-4 (Bull) aircraft.

Minor civilian airstrip. DoD products through 1997 suggest a position 5 km NW of village (72-38N 121-48E).  Satellite imagery is coarse and an airfield-like pattern appears here, maybe from abandoned construction in 1960s or 1970s.
A ghost airfield that was probably a planned bomber diversion or dispersal airfield.  It was probably abandoned around 1960.  Also see Dresba.

A major air base, by far the largest on Novaya Zemlya Island.  It is under the control of Arctic Control Group for use as a possible staging base for intercontinental bomber flights.  It is primarily an interceptor base, home to 641 Gv IAP.  It originally flew Yak-28P Firebar interceptors, but upgraded in the 1980s to 32 Su-27 interceptor aircraft.  It also had 2 Mi-8 helicopters in 1991.
Appears that runway is actually a highway strip; small parking tarmac.  ONC chart gave length of 1500 m, probably erroneous.
Position is approximate and location is suspected, probably on beach as a runwaylike clearway is located there.

Major airfield servicing medium-sized airliners.  Interceptor aircraft were based here in the 1970s.  Serves as a hub for North Pole tourist expeditions via Sredniy.  Well-paved and medium sized tarmac.   Designated for emergency airfield on cross-polar route.

Minor civilian airfield servicing the full range of prop transports and Tu-134.  High-resolution satellite imagery shows a dirt airfield but runway boundaries clearly marked, with a VASI system at both ends.

A remote, large bomber staging base that is now nonexistent.  Accounts exist of Tu-4s landing here with cargo, supplying what appears to be a missile testing range.  Airfield appears to be dismantled on satellite.  Conceivably concrete blocks may have been moved to Tiksi.

This appears to be a strategic airfield that was being developed in the 1950s but was abandoned.  Declassified satellite imagery is poor but some frames from the early 1960s show that the Tiksi North airfield was in use, not Tiksi West.

This is currently a major civilian airport serving the Arctic Ocean port of Tiksi.  However it has had an important military role since it was built in the 1950s, during which time it has been operated by OGA (Arctic Control Group) as a key staging facility for Soviet bombers to reach the U.S.  It is used regularly by Tu-95s in exercises, including one in 1999, in which bombers practice travelling to the Canadian arctic.  It is also home to 24 OTAE.
Minor airstrip handling general aviation aircraft.  There is some evidence that a concrete runway may have existed here at one time.  Runway is lined with markers.
Minor airstrip; position uncertain.
Minor airstrip.
Airstrip indicated on several aeronautical charts but not identifiable on coarse satellite imagery.
Civilian aifield; a couple of buildings on site.
Exact runway dimensions unavailable due to poor satellite imagery.  This is probably an industrial airfield.
Major airfield handling small transport aircraft.  Gravelled curved taxiways on north side suggest interceptors were based here.  Elevation given as 46 (TPC) and 35 (JNC).
Probably a civilian airfield.  Location is covered poorly by Google.
Appears to be an old WWII airfield.  Appeared on GNC-3 1974 edition but was not listed as jet-capable.

Former Cold War airfield which is the closest facility to the Norwegian border.  It became a helicopter base in the 1990s, operated by 258 OVE flying Mi-24K/R, Mi-35, and Mi-8 helicopters.  The helicopter regiment now appears to be gone, as Google high-res imagery showed no equipment based at the airfield, and the airfield is now in decay.  It appears there was an attempt to extend the runway to 2000 m at one time.

Minor, mediocre unattended airfield 83 km W of Murmansk, but with considerable runway length and small taxiway; is probably a forward deployment base.  Stands behind Pechenga as the closest base to Norway.

column2: Kilpyavr (US), Kilp-Yavr, Kil'p-Yar, Kilp-Yar, Polyarn'y, Polyarnyy
column49: Small interceptor base operated by 941 IAP and possibly 9 IAP.  The airfield initially operated MiG-19, Su-9, and MiG-23M during the 1960s.  It saw an upgrade to 38 Su-27 aircraft starting in 1985.  It should be noted that Polyarny is also the name of an airfield at Yakutsk.  Satellite imagery taken around 2003 showed numerous fighter jets based at this airfield.

This is one of the two largest airfields in the Murmansk region.  The main resident unit is the 987 MRAP, flying Tu-22M and Tu-16 as late as the early 1990s.  Also operating from the airfield is 24 ODLAPDD, flying Il-38s in the early 1990s.  The 3000 m runway has a 500 m overrun on the north side, and the airfield can accommodate over 40 bombers and a small number of fighters.  It lies 4 km south of Severomorsk.  This airfield was referred to as Vayenga in a 1955 CIA intelligence estimate, citing an airfield 9.5 miles northeast of Murmansk.

Small airfield halfway between Severomorsk and Murmansk (11 km NE of Murmansk).  It was home to 403 ODLAP, flying 24 Be-12 aircraft as late as the early 1990s.  It appears this regiment is now gone and the airfield is in a state of decay.  The runway originally had an 80 m width but only 40 m is usable.
Appears to be an old attack airfield or forward deployment field; no facilities.

Interceptor airfield operated by the 72 Gv IAP (given by some sources as 74 IAP), which was flying at least 31 MiG-31 aircraft in the early 1990s.  The facility is a simple concrete airfield built on a spit along the ocean.  There is some limited tarmac space for deployed aircraft.
Minor airstrip, position uncertain.
Services small transport aircraft.

Alykel is the only functional airfield around Norilsk.  It handles medium-sized airliners; 24 hour operations.  Designated as emergency airfield for cross-polar route.  Created in late 1950s, it has been a OGA (Arctic Control Group) facility providing staging for Soviet bombers to reach the U.S.  It has also served as an interceptor airfield, operated by 57 IAP flying at least 24 Su-15TM aircraft in 1991.
Airfield with unknown purpose about 8 km northeast of Norilsk.  Runway length is ambiguous due to severe deterioration of original runway.
A minor civilian airfield.  Runway boundaries not demarcated.
Minor civilian airfield.

Appears to be a never-completed bomber staging field, likely constructed around 1960.  Significant runway and taxiway patterns faintly appear on satellite.  Near village Mikhalkino.  Some sort of radar facility exists 14 km NW at 69-28N 161-23E.  Declassified satellite imagery shows the base existed in 1966 and was in good shape.
Services medium-sized airliners.  May have served as interceptor base for northeast Arctic.  Elevation is given as 3 (TPC) and 14 (JNC).
Confidence in position is low to moderate; this is the only possible airstrip in area indicated by TPC C-7B.
Handles medium-sized airliners.  Parking for 15 aircraft at main terminal near center+AC650; 13 additional spots with helicopter stands at adjacent apron to northwest.

Appears to be a base for transport aircraft; large pads in remote taxiway loops.  It is operated by an attack fighter regiment, 279 OMSHAP, which flew 41 Su-25, 4 Su-25UB, and 5 Su-25UTG, 27 Yak-38, and one Yak-38U in the early 1990s.
Unknown airfield; single 500 x 50 m ramp.  May be abandoned.

This is the single most important strategic aviation base in the western Arctic, located 92 km south of Murmansk.  It is a major bomber airfield with wide runways and taxiways.  It has been operated by OGA (Arctic Control Group) to serve as a staging base for intercontinental bombers.   It was home to 924 MRAP that flew Tu-95MS, Tu-22M, and Tu-16.  An attack presence is provided by 88 OMAPIB, flying 31 MiG-27 and 9 MiG-23 aircraft in the early 1990s.  The 967 ODRAP flew reconnaissance with the Tu-16R.  Olenegorsk is headquarters for 5 MRAD and has served as a temporary summer facility for the Siaulyay Tu-126 AWACS airplane.  Satellite imagery from 2003 showed numerous Tu-22 aircraft.  Olenya is the name given on CAICA charts.
Civilian airport and probably a former military helicopter base.
Very minor airfield, may be abandoned.
Accommodates small transport aircraft.  Position confidence is moderate and within 1 mile due to high albedo and poor contrast of surrounding area.
Small engineered airfield with one or two buildings and a few narrow taxiways.
Handles small transport aircraft.  Ramp space on satellite imagery is rather large.
Small civilian airstrip.  Exact position and alignment uncertain due to poor satellite imagery.
Services small transport planes
Services small transport aircraft. Elevation given as 6 (TPC) and 30 (JNC).  Runway width estimated from Google images.
Airfield location uncertain.
Airfield location uncertain.
Small gravel airstrip.

Major airfield with 1100 x 80 m concrete tarmac.  Gravel overrun suggests runway was to eventually be extended to 3000 m.  Operated by OGA (Arctic Control Group), this is an arctic staging base for intercontinental bomber flights.  In the spring of 1952, CIA reports inicated that the Soviet Union was operating the TU-4 (a strategic bomber based on a re-engineered B-29 Superfortress) from both Mys Shmidta and Provideniya.
This interceptor base was home to 431 IAP and possibly 470 IAP, flying Su-15 and Su-27 aircraft in the early 1990s.

Older, small airfield about 11 miles southwest of Olenogorsk.  Contains curvy parallel taxiway with a number of small revetments.  It was home to the interceptor regiment 174 GV IAP flying MiG-25PDS in the 1980s and as many as 29 MiG-31 in the early 1990s.  The 98 ORAP flew the MiG-25RB, Su-17, Su-24MR, and MiG-31.
Small civilian airport with 130 x 80 m tarmac and some concrete parking pads.
Appears to be older airfield with single tarmac area.  Handles medium-sized airliners.  Closed 1994.  The 227 OVE REB flew the Mi-8 helicopter from Kirovska.
Located 165 km SE of Murmansk, this airfield contains 20 revetments, each 100 m apart.  No tarmac space.  Elevation given as 149 m (ONC, 1988).
Minor airfield, probably a decaying forward bomber staging base from 1960s/1970s.  No buildings.  Elevation given as 113 m (ONC, 1988).
Small civilian airfield.  Exact dimensions unknown due to poor satellite imagery.
Either a helicopter airfield or a small civil airstrip.  Minor taxiways.  May be abandoned.
Small airfield near Kanevka on the Kola Peninsula.
Severely neglected airfield, barely visible; probably a forward staging field in the 1950s.
Major combat airfield with 2000 m runway in remote area of Barents Sea coast, probably built in 1940s or 1950s for northern defense, now almost completely dismantled.
Minor airfield serving Chizha.
Mostly a civilian field, but runway length and tarmac space suggest possible military use.  The only airfield on the coast between Arkhangel and Novaya Zemlya.
Nothing on high-res imagery; this location may not in fact exist.
Services small airliners.

Operated by OGA (Arctic Control Group), this is a staging base created in the late 1950s for intercontinental bombers.  The main runway is 80 m wide.  The 364 OSAE operated from this location.  OGA (Arctic Control Group).  Photos exist on russianplanes.net of Il-76 and Tu-95 aircraft.
Poor Google imagery; indeterminate.
Services medium-sized airliners.  Probably a mining settlement.  Located in remote area of Siberia in Vorkuta region, 90 km southeast of Cape Kameny.
Peculiar appearance on satellite; runway appears to be extremely wide, but this may just be an artifact.  Accommodates small transports.
Accommodates medium-sized airliners.  Well-paved and maintained, however is isolated on an island and depends on ice crossing or ferry service.
Small civilian airfield.

Airfield appears to have been in much better condition in the 1950s with minor concrete runway; this runway is in poor condition now and is filled in with gravel in many areas.  Only about 1150 of hard surface exist on the 1600 m runway.  Several small maintenance buildings exist on the airfield.
Civilian; services small transport prop planes.
Civilian airfield, most likely.
Minor civilian airstrip serving the Omolon River town of Mandrikovo.
Handles small transport aircraft.  About 20 km southwest of Bilibino.
Small paved airstrip servicing a very remote Chukot mining town.

During the 1950s Alakurtti was suspected as being the most likely candidate for development of a major strategic bomber base; this did not occur and Olenegorsk became the primary bomber base.  It was home to 4th Naval Bomber Regiment flying Su-24 aircraft.  Helicopter services were provided by 485 OVP flying Mi-24 and Mi-8 helicopters.
Minor airstrip with only turnarounds and a 400 meter central taxiway.  Appears neglected.  Was probably for forward fighter deployments in the 1950s and 1960s.
New Kirov airport, services Tu-134 in summer and An-24 in winter.
Small civilian airfield serving the port town of Umba.
Appears to be an Army helicopter operations field.
Small airfield.
Location and dimensions uncertain due to poor satellite imagery.
Location and dimensions uncertain due to poor satellite imagery.
Minor airfield, barely visible on satellite.
Small civilian airstrip.
Minor airstrip; position estimated as there are no good candidates on satellite imagery.
Minor civilian airfield.  Runway heading is estimated, as there are two possible short runways.
Minor civilian airstrip.  Position and runway heading are estimated (satellite imagery poor).
Minor civilian airstrip.
Minor airstrip; exact location uncertain.
Services medium-size airliners.
Minor dirt airstrip.
Services small transport aircraft.  Elevation given as 46 m (ONC, 1988).
Primarily a civilian airfield, handling medium-sized airliners.  No military features.  Emergency airfield for cross-polar route.
Poor Google imagery; indeterminate.
Handles medium-sized airliners.  Ample tarmac space and well-maintained.
Handles small transport aircraft.  Extremely spartan layout with one perpendicular taxiway to parking area.
Services all types of aircraft.  Built on 4000 x 190 m gravel base; first 100 m of runway unusable for takeoff.  Emergency airfield for the cross-polar route.
Small civilian airfield serving the Lena River town of Bakhaynay.
Services small transport aircraft.
Small civilian airstrip.
Handles small transport aircraft.  Extremly spartan layout (one ramp with right-angle taxiway to it). [Honuu]
Small airstrip serving the small town of Buor-Sysy.
Minor civilian airstrip servicing Baimka valley region.
Small civilian airstrip.
Purpose of airfield unknown due to poor satellite resolution.  Appeared on 1974 GNC-3 chart.
Very small airfield serving the town of Kalevala.
Not much left except bare dirt.  Appeared on 1970s-era GNC charts.  Poor satellite imagery makes it impossible to determine what the purpose of this airfield was.
Small civilian airport with paved asphalt runway and capable of handling the Tu-134 and other small passenger jets.
Poor Google imagery; indeterminate.
Well-maintained small airstrip; probably a helicopter operating location.
Position and heading are approximate due to inferior satellite imagery.
Handles small transport planes.
Minor dirt airstrip.
Runway heading uncertain due to poor satellite imagery.
Small transport aircraft serviced.  Bare-bones utilitarian layout.
Handles small airliners.

This airfield has served primarily as an AWACS operations base for the Arctic regions.  The airfield has about 12 hardstands, small tarmacs.  The runway is only marked out to 2850 m with a 150 m threshold.  The 144 OAPDRLO flew the A-50 Mainstay starting in 1989.
Accommodates small transports.
Handles large airliners (up to Il-62 and Il-86).
Major dirt airstrip with several pads.  Appears that a concrete runway may have been present, possibly up to 2200 m long.
Unknown purpose.  There are eight pads for aircraft.  However the layout does not indicate that the airfield was paved.  This is a good candidate for examining declassified Corona or other imagery.
Civilian airfield.
Accommodates small transport aircraft.
Services medium-size airliners.
Handles small transports.
Very small utilitarian runway in remote area, crossing a road.
Small utilitarian airfield.
Airfield near Zyryanka; difficult to ascertain exact position on satellite.  Some buildings still remain.  Connected Alaska to Oimyakon during WWII Lend-Lease.
Small airstrip west of Zyryanka; no buildings noted.
Minor airfield serving Siberian mining town of Glukharinyy.  Appears airfield may have originally had a 1750 x 200 m gravel runway, however it has seriously deteriorated.
Small civilian gravel airfield.
Small civilian airstrip with gravel parking apron.  Services upper Anadyr River region.
Appears to be a small ice strip on an enclosed lake.  Indicated on 1977 GNC-6 chart.
Small gravel airstrip along seashore.  During the 1950s Uel Kal was suspected of being a candidate for construction of a major Soviet bomber staging base.
Airfield is shown on 1977 GNC-6 chart, but no clear location found on satellite imagery (poor quality).
Small airstrip with tarmac, almost in center of town of Lavrentiya.

Interceptor airfield which became operational in 1957.  The 265 IAP flew Su-15 and Su-27 aircraft as late as the 1990s.  Pilots Slabodchikov, Yu. Novozhilov, A. Genberg, and Kerefov in aircraft from this base forced a Korean Airlines 707 down in 1978.  The airfield appears to be in a serious condition of decay and is likely not operational.
Very poor image quality but position is confirmed by images posted on the Internet.
Very small gravel airstrip with tiny ramp.  Poor quality Google imagery.
Small civilian airfield with parking apron.

Talagi, which opened in 1963, contains considerable tarmac space, very large hangars, and is primarily a civilian airport.  The 518 IAP operated Tu-128 interceptor aircraft starting around 1966 through the early 1980s, then upgraded to MiG-31 aircraft in the 1980s.  The regiment interacted with Tu-126 from Siaulyay.
Minor general aviation airfield.
Utility airfield

Kholm appears to be a typical base with medium-sized revetments along a parallel taxiway.  Nuclear bomber base.  The 574 MRAP flew the Tu-16, but operated as many as 20 Tu-22M as late as the early 1990s.
Small civilian airstrip.
Small airstrip.
Handles prop transport aircraft.
Exact locations and dimensions uncertain due to poor satellite image quality.
Location and dimensions uncertain due to cloud shadow over airfield on satellite image.
Dimensions doubtful due to poor satellite imagery, but airfield is definitely shown.
Small airfield serving the logging town of Koynas.
Small airfield serving Vozhgora.  Some sources give a grossly erroneous location.
Large dirt clearing with no well-defined runway.
Small civilian airstrip about 50 km south of Pechora.  Very close to Ust Soplesk airfield.
Small civilian airstrip about 50 km south of Pechora.  Very close to Ust Voya airfield.
Services small transport aircraft.
Appears to be a small civilian airfield that can receive medium-sized planes.
Minor civilian airstrip.

Handles small transport aircraft.  Paved runway and one small tarmac.  This was part of the Provideniya-Markovo-Yakutsk leg of the WWII Lend-Lease program.  A 2428 m length comes from an unknown source.

Services small transport aircraft; 4 paved parking spaces.  Short gravel airfield probably incapable of military use.  Has received Tu-95MR flights.  In the spring of 1952, the Soviet Union was operating the TU-4 (a strategic bomber based on a re-engineered B-29 Superfortress) from Mys Shmidta and Provideniya.  Avia.ru gives a length of 2000 m and elevation of 16 m.
Location uncertain.  Appears on 1977 GNC-6 chart.  May be the airfield that served Anadyr before Ugolny was built.

This is a staging base, operated by OGA (Arctic Control Group), for intercontinental bombers (Tu-22, etc).  In 2001 it accepted Tu-95MS and Il-78 aircraft on exercise from Engels.  It regularly practices flights to the Canadian arctic.  Single parallel taxiway with two 600 x 80 m tarmacs.  Civilian parking tarmac can accommodate 25 aircraft.
Probably a helicopter base.
1960s-era military base; listed on 1974 GNC-3 as a major aerodrome with jet facilities.  Located 9 km SE of Kyargozero town.
Appears to be an uncompleted deployment field for large aircraft, perhaps used for attack aircraft training flights in the 1980s.  A highway crosses in the middle.  Modest tarmac area; no pads.
Probably a former grass airfield at the town of Onega.  Position uncertain.

An interceptor base operated by 524 IAP which flew MiG-25 into the early 1990s.  Two major revetment areas holding over 15 aircraft each. Provides supporting cover for Andozero and Arkhangelsk. [Obozerskiy Southeast] (US)
Runway dimension estimated; albedo too high in area.
Small civilian airstrip.
Services medium-sized airliners.  Also near Sosnogorsk.
Services small airliners. Very spartan, utilitarian layout.
Handles small transport aircraft.
Services small prop transports.
Unknown airfield; discovered by accident.  It may be intended to support the petroleum industry in this region.  Airfield name Kislor East is an estimated name.
Services small prop transports.
Handles small airliners.
Services small transport aircraft.
This is a very straight run of road that is marked on a 1987 ONC chart.  It is unknown whether this is actually an airfield.
Small dirt airstrip serving the Yenisey River town of Verkhne-Imbatskoye with small 18 x 16 m concrete pad.
Services small transport aircraft.
Handles small transports.
Accommodates small transport aircraft.
A number of unimproved runway candidates exist here; using best candidate and best location on TPC.
Minor gravel airstrip in Yakutsk region.
Large dirt airfield.
Well-defined airstrip with turnarounds and parking tarmac.
Small civilian airstrip with parknig area and hangar.
Very small gravel airstrip with tiny ramp.
Former 1960s-era airfield.  Shown on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities.  Almost nothing remains; geometrics are almost not visible.
Appears to be a former military airfield.  Some Panoramio photos of this airfield exist.  Very poor Google satellite imagery.
Logistical base for Plesetsk launch facility.  Near the center of prohibited area ULP1.
Paved civilian airstrip.
Civilian airfield.
Paved civilian airstrip serving region northwest of Kotlas.  Likely capable of handling Yak-42 and Tu-134.
Minor airstrip with few structures.
Suspected location and dimensions only due to poor satellite imagery.
Services medium-sized airliners.
Accommodates medium-sized airliners.
Accommodates widebody airliners.  Width given as 45 m at avia.ru.
Small dirt airstrip at the Yeloguy River town of Kellog.
Outline or location of airstrip uncertain; appears it may simply be along a straight road in a clear area north of town.
An old airstrip that appears to be overgrown and may not be serviceable.
Handles medium-sized airliners.  24-hour operation.  Serves as emergency airfield for cross-polar route.
Fairly large airfield; contains a single large 300-meter long tarmac area.
Dirt runway appears to be former concrete runway; well-maintained.  US DoD reports 4237 m (13900 ft) length.
Major passenger hub for eastern Siberia; parks up to 35 mixed aircraft.  Services all types of airliners.
Small dirt airstrip with one hangar.
Accommodates small transport aircraft.
Minor civilian airfield.  Location and dimensions uncertain due to snow cover in imagery.

Runway is well-maintained; may be paved.  Marked as military on US DoD charts.  Connected Zyryanka (UESU) to Oimyakon during WWII Lend-Lease.  Google imagery showed only some small single-engine prop planes.

Services small transport aircraft.  Appears only about 1800 m paved, however airfield appears engineered enough to be considered a marginal major facility and service small jet airliners. Spartan utilitarian configuration.
Civilian airstrip serving the town of Garmanda.
Minor unpaved airfield on the other side of the Penzhina River from the town, thus serviced only by boat or ice crossing.
Runway surface not clear on satellite; clearing area is noted.
Destroyed; some faint outlines still visible.  Shown on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities.
World War II airfield now bulldozed to the ground.  Shown on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities.
Services small airliners.  Minor airfield with 12 parking stands and small tarmac space.  The 159 IAP flew Su-27 through the 1990s.  The 991 IAP flew MiG-25 interceptors.
Small paved airfield.
Runway heading uncertain due to coarse satellite imagery.
Minor civilian airstrip.
Minor civilian airstrip.
Airfield servicing prop transports.
Small civilian airstrip.

Services medium-sized airliners; terminal is on northwest side with 10 large parking spaces and 9 small ones; maintenance area is on northeast side.  24-hour operations.  CAICA 2000 gave elevation of 104 m.
Civilian airport probably constructed around 1990.
Position unknown; ONC reports it on north fringes of town.
Civilian airport.
May have been a MiG-25 base, as a MiG-25 is on display in the town.
Services medium-size airliners.  CAICA 2000 gives 42 m elevation elsewhere.
Civilian airport in central Siberian region with long asphalt runway, services airline traffic.
Services medium-sized airliners.
Position unknown.
Position doubtful; airfield is indicated on a 1987 ONC.

Small engineered airfield with concrete parking area.  Handles small transport aircraft.
Major paved airfield with rudimentary taxiways and small parking apron.  Services medium-sized airliners.
Airfield on Ostrov Moshchnyy, island in Baltic, served as a WWII airfield for Russia 1940-44.
Naval military airfield with 10 medium revetments and 12 large ones.  This airfield guards the approach to St. Petersburg (Leningrad) from Helsinki, Finland.
Basic military airfield northwest of St. Petersburg (Leningrad).  On 8 March 1988 a hijacked Tu-154 parking at this airfield was stormed. The airfield is now abandoned.
Important airfield during WWII.  Was a prime site for helicopters and light aircraft in conjunction with the development of the island. (AviaMK)[17]  The military now leases it to a small airclub.
Old, small fighter airfield with crude extension from 2000 to 2500 m.  Located only 90 km north of St Petersburg (Leningrad).
Abandoned military airfield in St. Petersburg (Leningrad) area; a road intersects the runway.
Houses mostly small transport planes.  An12/26 base (AviaMK).
Small fighter/utility airfield.  Several hangars and a long narrow tarmac.  The base moved from MiG-23 to Su-27 in 1988-89.
Small civilian airfield with parking ramp.
Small civilian airfield, small parking apron.
Small civilian airfield.
Small interceptor airfield.  Given as Savati.
Small civilian airfield with 100 x 100 m parking apron and a few buildings.
Small civilian airstrip.
Appears that this was originally 2000m.  Definite civilian airport with one tarmac. Handles small transport aircraft.
Services up to medium-sized airliners.
Large civilian airport with asphalt runway, handling up to some widebody aircraft.  Services gas production region
Large tarmac (400 x 100 m) in civilian configuration; services small transports.
Small dirt airfield; some old concrete on part of the runway.
Small airfield along shore of Yenisey River.
Well-maintained but very small airfield with parking pad.
Services small transports.
Civilian.  Cleared out to 3 km, suggesting runway length may have been longer decades ago.
Handles small airliners.
Services general aviation.  Small utilitarian layout.  Airport is well-maintained; may actually be concrete pavement.

Services small transport aircraft.  Located on sand islet.

Civilian airport with 33 large parking spaces near main terminal. Small military pad.  Older runway was 2850 m.
Actual pavement appears to be 2500 m.
Typical fighter base.
Location suggested by AviaMK; not confirmed.
Abandoned 1960s-era airfield, listed as a major aerodrome on a 1974 GNC-3 with jet facilities.  Geometrics now barely visible.  Length of 10900 ft obtained from ONC D-3.
Services small transport aircraft.

International airport for St. Petersburg (Leningrad).  Terminal area services 64 medium/large aircraft; Apron 3 on northeast side handles 22 aircraft.  Rwy 10L/28R was closed in 2005.  First 100 m of all runways unusable for takeoff.

Closed military facility 10 km west of Pulkovo International Airport.  Today it has only 100 stored Mil8's and had one active An26.  May have been named Gorelovo and renamed in early 1990s.  (Thanks to AviaMK)  A closeup photo exists on airliners.net (638374).
Handles small airliners.  Very active military base with Il18/22/38 and Antonov's

Small airfield 65 km south of St. Petersburg (Leningrad).  Nuclear bomber base according to NRDC.  United States inspection was conducted here in 11 February 1992, at which time Su-24 aircraft were in service.  Google Earth imagery shows several Su-24 aircraft parked.
Appears to be a bare-bones forward deployment base.  Cut tightly into forest.
Appears to be an abandoned major airfield.  Dimensions approximate due to satellite imagery overlaps.
Services small airliners.

Large base for long-range aircraft; 20 revetments in remote area and large tarmac along parallel taxiway.  Built in 1963, Kipelovo was a major source of Tu-142 flights overshadowing the U.S. fleet in the Atlantic.  <http://www.vologda18.narod.ru/>
Location uncertain.
Medium-sized airfield with several buildings and hangars.
Small paved civilian airfield with parking area and administration buildings.
Mostly services helicopters.
Position uncertain due to poor Google satellite imagery.
Barely visible, if at all, on satellite.  May be just a helipad.  ONC seems to indicate that it exists.
Small transport aircraft.  Li-2 are based here.
Concrete runway appears to be in decay.
Abandoned military base; probably an interceptor base from 1950s/1960s.  Shows distinct hardened taxiway pattern and evidence of extensive military buildings. Services small transport aircraft.

A major airport that parks 30 jets on its apron.  It was built starting in 1961, with work completed in 1963.  It services nearly all types of jets.  The western overrun measures 600x42 m long but is no longer usable since approach lights are installed here; this overrun has a turnaround and it appears it formed part of an older runway that was moved east and expanded in the 1980s or 1990s.

Handles most prop transports.  Regular passenger Il-14 were flying here in 1950s-60s.  In 70s-80s it was a busy airport for charter operations (An-2, Mi-4, Mi-8, etc) that served geological expeditions, firefighters, and local routes.  Currently there are An-2s, Mi-8s, and a helicopter maintenance facility. (Thanks to Alexey Skibin)
Services small transports.
Appears a new runway is under construction at this location.
Unpaved civilian airfield along ocean shore.
Well-maintained civilian airfield on Hiiumaa Island.
Airfield on Saaremaa Island plowed under and geometrics barely visible.  Listed on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities, so was conceivably a 1950s-era front line interceptor base.
Small civilian airport.
Small fighter airfield with a few revetments.  [Khaapsapu] [Khaapsalu]
Basic fighter airfield. Civilian terminal.
Appears to be a former attack deployment base.  It has gradually been converted into farmland and little remains.  In 1974 it was listed on the GNC-3 chart as a jet-capable facility.
Former military base.  Very faint geometrics still visible.
Probably an abandoned front-line or maritime bomber base from 1940s or 1950s.  Some remains of runways and taxiways can be seen.

column48: 132 TBAP (Tu-22M3, 1991)[#2] (Tu-16).  192 VTAP (Il-76M, until 1990, then relocated to Tver)[#4].  196 VTAP (Il-76)[#4].
column49: Fairly extensive base with 24 large revetments and over 30 small ones.  This may be civilian now as it was listed as an emergency airfield on a 1993 Jeppesen chart.
Small civilian airport.
This medium-sized Su-24 base is located 63 km S of Ivangorod.  Nuclear bomber base according to NRDC.

column2: Sol'tsy (US), Soltsy, Solcy, Solcy 2, Sol'tsakh, Soltsakh
column49: Located 72 km SW of Novgorod.  Large revetments, with separate area of 9 hardened areas about 1 mile from airfield.  Headquarters 326th Heavy Bomber Division (326 TBAD), tenant 840 TBAP is subordinate to it.  Nuclear base according to NRDC.
30 large revetments in sprawling taxiway pattern, suitable for large transports.
Handles small transport planes.
Services small transport aircraft.  Small utilitarian layout.
Handles small airliner traffic. [Lyangisovo]
NEED ONC D-5
Handles small transport aircraft.  Extremely unimproved dirt runway.
Well-developed civilian airfield with concrete 180 x 55 m tarmac.
Civilian airfield.  Simple utilitarian paved layout with 500 x 50 m tarmac.  Handles prop airliners.
Minor civilian airstrip.
Small civilian airstrip.
Appears to be a very rudimentary civilian airfield.  Runway is either dirt or asphalt.
Well designed utilitarian airport.
Paved, minimal utilitarian layout.  Small transports.
Simple paved utilitarian layout.  Handles small airliners.
Major regional facility handling all sizes of airliners.  Very large concrete runway with 500 x 200 m tarmac.
Small airfield near town center.
Very small airport; runway not directly visible on satellite but disturbed area measures 2000 m long.
Very small civilian airport; may be unattended.
This is a major combat aircraft base that has been abandoned and dismantled.  All that appears now is farmland.  It was probably a forward attack deployment base.
Major military airfield that has been plowed under.  Geometrics plainly visible.  Listed on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities.  Located just 3 km inside Estonian border, near Latvia border.
Medium air base with 27 large revetments in complex, sprawling taxiway layout.  Terminal area services 13 medium/large planes and 20 small planes.  No ILS.

Large air base 57 km south of Pskov.  Nuclear bomber facility with 15 very large revetments on east side and about 30 small revetments on west side.  As many as 63 Tu-16s were based here.  5501 Unit is a direct reporting unit.
Major military airfield in 1950s, probably demolished in 1980s.  Little trace of it remains.
Large reworks facility for Antonov and Ilyushin aircraft.  Google Earth showed several Il-76 transport jets parked on the tarmac.  Listed on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities.

Fighter base with 3 groups of fan revetments.  On 1 June 2005 a MiG-31 based here crash-landed here; the crew was only injured.  It appears that the airfield is undergoing major construction.  Only a 1550 m runway remained, but numerous MiG-31 aircraft were parked here.
Small interceptor base with about 10 alert pads for fighter aircraft and some other pads and tarmac space.
Services An-2, Mi-8.
Services medium-sized airliners.  Medium airfield, few revetments; 415 IAP disbanded in 1992 and the planes were sent to Rzhev.

Large transport operations airfield with hangars and significant tarmac space.  A civilian airfield with 2500 m runway exists 7 km S of Ivanovo.  Runway built 1935, upgraded 1965.  Received Russia's first Il-76 delivery 3 June 1974.
column50: NE of Ivanovo.  An22 reworks (former base) IL76 AN12 base with most VVS A50(IL76) AWACs based Small military Museum  (AviaMK)

column49: Services prop transports.
Abandoned; little trace remains.

Until 1965 this was the major civilian airport in Perm City and handled medium-sized and small aircrafts Li-2, Il-14, An-24, An-2, Yak-12, then the major airport was relocated in Bolshoye Savino military airfield[19].  The airfield is abandoned and used mainly for motor-racing; all the area will be built up soon by apartment houses[19].

Mixed use airfield with small number of fighter and bomber pads.  Services medium-sized airliners, with 39 parking spots near terminal and cargo area.  During Cold War operated MiG-25, Yak-25, Yak-28.  Received MiG-31s in 1991.  Length given as 2500 m on a 1998 Jeppesen.  The 87th IAD (Fighter Air Division) that was born in 1952 in the new airfield Bolshoye-Savino.  The 87th IAD (Fighter Air Division) was created in 1952 at the new airfield Bolshoye-Savino; construction was under personal control of Marshal Zhukov, who was exiled by Stalin after WW2 in Urals to take command of the Ural military district.
Probably a military airfield due to several separate tarmac areas.
This airstrip existed in the early 1980s but probably disappeared due to construction.
Services large airliners.  The DAFIF source has a slightly differing location as it uses the tip juncture of the two runways.
Small civilian airport with parking tarmac.
Listed as new landing site in 2009 CAICA chart changes.
Listed as new landing site in 2009 CAICA chart changes.
Listed as closed site in 2009 CAICA chart changes.
Minor, spartan airfield.  Accommodates small transports.  Avia.ru gives a longitude of 072-16E.
Small civilian airfield; no taxiways, small tarmac.
Handles small transport aircraft.  This was part of the Yakutsk-Kirensk-Krasnoyarsk leg of the WWII Lend-Lease program.

Services small transports.  The full length of the airfield is 2350 m, but a 600 x 40 m concrete stretch on the northeast side is in poor condition and is not part of the marked runway area.  May be a former combat airfield.
Appears to be a minor industrial airfield.
Small unimproved airfield on west shores of Kamchatka.
Services small transports.
Probably a civilian airfield, but with ramp space.
Listed on 1974 GNC-3 as having jet facilities, so it may have had military use; runways are substandard length, though.  Appears on 1993 Jeppesen chart as emergency airfield.  Parks 9 jets.
Abandoned airfield.  Only 4 km from southern border.
Distinctly visible on satellite; has one small parking area on north side.

Spartan military airfield with single long ramp and reveted area.  Starting in the 1960s the 668 BAP flew the Yak-28 Brewer[#34].  The unit became 668 MShAP and by the 1990s was flying 30 Su-24 aircraft.  Also based here was the 240 MSHAP flying 29 Su-24 aircraft.

West side has 11 large revetments (one Il-76 was noted on satellite).  East side is civilian terminal complex with 39 large/medium spaces and at least 20 spaces for small aircraft.  400 meter overrun at both ends of runway.

Probably a forward deployment attack base.  The airfield is in a severe state of decay and trees are growing throughout the runway area.  The airfield is marginally operational though and several general aviation planes, including an An-2, are still parked there.
Minor airfield, maybe WWII vintage, appears on old ONC D-3 chart.  Air base, if present, was overgrown by forest; no trace remains.
Small civilian airstrip with one tarmac and some buildings.

Former 1950s-era military base, now unused.  Ring taxiway with small revetments. High-res sat only shows two general-aviation planes parked.  Large Technical School until 90's with one of each major aircraft type, most broken up around 96/7 (AviaMK).

Airfield may have had military use in the 1950s and 1960s.  However now, 1-meter Google images indicate that it is primarily a non-aviation industrial park, and only about five small general aviation planes are based here.

Fighter or interceptor airfield southeast of Riga, built in late-1970s for an Su-24 regiment.  Transferred from Russia to Latvia in 1994 and now forms the core of operations for the Latvian Air Force.  (Thanks to AviaMK)
This combat airfield was home to 886 ORAP which had the Su-17 and flew Yak-28R starting in the mid 1970s [#34] but upgraded to the Su-24MR.
Almost nothing remains, not even geometrics, except a cleared-out area.
Civilian; accommodates small airliners.
Appears to have been built as an interceptor base, with mostly fighter revetments.  MiG-29 crashed 12 May 2005 near base.  Satellite imagery showed at least 28 MiG-29 aircraft on site.
Probably abandoned in 1970s; treeline of forest surrounds former airfield.  Confidence of site on satellite is mediocre.
Tu-128 depot airfield during Cold War.  Appears to service minor amounts of large military aircraft, including MiG-29 aircraft, with about 100 of these parked.
Abandoned airfield.
Large military transport base.  Currently houses all of Russia's remaining An-22 fleet. IL76 base, with some An12 stored. (AviaMK)
Klin is a field between Moscow and Tver with many military transport types IL76/An12/26/Tu134 etc and airfield was active until recently. Many aircraft still here but most are stored.  (AviaMK)
Small utility airfield.  Has a Tu-124 preserved outside the field (AviaMK).  L-29 jets have operated out of this airport.
Civilian airport for Ivanovo.  Handles medium-sized airliners.
Old fighter airfield northeast of Moscow.  Does not appear on latest JNC at all, though an NDB exists.
Forestry commision and VVS An26 base.  Displaced threshold leaves 1700 m for northbound takeoff.
Old airfield located alongside lake; no structures or facilities.  Not to be confused with Moscow/Chkalovskoye, Kaliningrad/Chkalovsk, or Omsk/Chlalovsk.
Located 38 km northwest of Nizhny Novgorod (Gorky).  Air base has numerous revetments and hardened areas, but appears to be decommissioned.
Military base with Mig25/31. Local aircraft plant with aircraft based here. (AviaMK)
Civil terminal with very large apron that can accommodate 44 aircraft. 24-hour operations.  Several Ministry of Interior IL76's based here. (AviaMK)
Handles small airliners.
Services medium-sized airliners.
Small fighter airfield.
Handles small airliners.
Minor airfield.
Services a wide range of civilian airliners; parks up to 65 aircraft.  A Su-9 from this airfield intercepted Gary Powers U-2 in 1960 but was unable to shoot it down; the U-2 crashed near Povarnya.
Small airfield 5 km south of larger Koltsovo airport.  Handles small transport aircraft.  As of 1981 the runway was 1300 x 40 m [CAICA].
Medium-sized military airfield with long 2600 x 70 m tarmac.
Large tarmac area. Il-76 base.
Listed as new landing site in 2009 CAICA chart changes.
Civilian airport but may be hybrid.  Services medium-size airliners.
Civilian airfield with minor facilities for small number of fighter aircraft. Source [#1] seems to list 712 IAP at Kansk but lists Achinsk in parentheses.

Major civil airport opened in 1980.  Kras Air main base with large airliners separate military area. (AviaMK)  Main runway apron holds 47 aircraft; small runway has own terminal and met office, and holds 94 small aircraft.

Former airfield that has been converted into a boulevard lined with apartment complexes.  There was an An-2 maintenance facility, which is now gone.  It was a utilitarian airfield with An-2/An-24/An-6, probably now based at Emelyanovo.
Small civilian airstrip; may be abandoned.  One area of the airfield contains an older concrete extension that is 80 m wide but has fallen into disrepair.
Fighter base with about 10 remote revetments.  Old 2000 m runway, no taxiways, exists between city and airfield.
Mixed use airfield, servicing medium-sized airliners with 32 parking spaces. Also a number of branched fighter revetments.  CAICA 2000 gave elevation as 491 m.
Services small airliners.
Services small airliners.
Civilian airport.
Civilian airport with dirt runway.
Paved airport with parking apron.  Civilian.
Civilian airport.
Wide paved runway and parking apron.  Civilian airport.
Services up to medium-sized airliners.  Serves as emergency field for the cross-polar route.

Possible airfield presumably abandoned during construction in the 1960s.  Listed on 1977 GNC.  Clearline around airfield measures 3500 m in length and is well-maintained.  Due to snow cover, unable to ascertain whether airfield exists.

Small but significant interceptor airfield covering northern Kamchatka.  About 12 fighter revetments and some narrow tarmac space.  Services Kura military proving area (Klyuchi-20)[12][13], an ICBM impact area 130 km to the northeast at 57-20N 161-50E.  Was photographed by U-2s starting June 1957.

Medium-sized airfield handling small transport planes.  Taxiway and apron suggests possible military use in past, though substandard runway length suggests it is not of significant military importance.
Civilian airport with single apron containing 11 parking spaces; facility is equipped with ILS.
Small general aviation &utilitarian filed with An2/28 based. (AviaMK)  An 1825 m runway is marked on old charts; satellite seems to show that current runway is a segment of the old runway.

Bomber base with revetments for 40 large aircraft and alert area with about 10 fighter-size revetments.   Sole operating location for Tu-126 Moss in 1970s, used to extend early warning radar coverage into the Baltic Ocean.  Civilian terminal north side; facility is listed by Jeppesen as "International".
Probably a forward bomber base; single loop revetment area with mixed bomber and fighter pads.

column48: 128 GV VTAP (Il-76, An-22)[#4].  600 VTAP (Il-76, An-22, until 1992, relocated to Shadrin).[#4]  144 OAPDRLO (A-50) prob this Kaunas base until 1989.
column49: Transport base 45 km north of Kaunas.  Has 28 large pads.  Listed as civilian on DAFIF.

column2: Panevezys, Panyavezhis, Panevejis, Panevezhis, Pajuostis, Tulpe
column49: Transport base; very large ring taxiway 2 km in diameter.  There are 32 large revetments.  Received USSR's first Il-76M on 27 August 1977.  Relocated in 1992 to Orenburg.
Linear ramp with 24 parking spaces.  May be a military base.
Small fighter base with a few unimproved revetments and small tarmac space.  Base is now completely abandoned.  [Lociki]
Medium air base.  Three loop areas with 15 revetments each, and central tarmac area.  305 BAP responsible to 1 BAD (Lida).
Cold War air base with sprawling taxiway area and pads for about 40 aircraft.
Purely civilian, utilitarian airfield.
Small airfield complex with single large tarmac.
Accommodates small airliners up to Tu-134.
Sport field (AviaMK).  Small air base.
Located near Moscow, Kubinka is operated as a showcase air force base.  An12/26 base home of two display teams (AviaMK).
Airfield servicing small prop aircraft.

A 1960s-era airbase completely plowed over into pasture.  A degree confluence is along the southern tarmac; two confluence hunters did not see any remains or even suspect them, but photos clearly show suspicious clearings and revetments.
Site of a 1940s bomber airfield with a regiment specializing in Arctic navigation.
Has serviced most of Russia's international connections since the 1960s.  The north side has 58 parking spaces; the south side 42 spaces.
Old airstrip now a pasture between developed areas; may be of historical (WWII) significance.  Located only 7 km SE of Sheremetyevo International Airport.
General aviation field (AviaMK).

This was actually an airport bus station for the last 20 odd years, but is no longer active and today the whole site is a giant building site. It is home to a large number of stored aircraft from Sukhoi OKB, Mig OKB (this has moved to Luchovitsy).  A proper Museum is being prepared on the site in a park south of the runway cross over. Khodinka is where all IL18 and variants were built.  Was used in 1941 by 12 IAP. (Thanks to AviaMK)
Helipad faciity; a number of Mil helicopters can be seen on satellite imagery.

Services all types of airliners.  Vnukovo 1 terminal has 60 parking spots. ARP 400 Tu154 reworks facility, VIP ramp for government aircraft. IL96/62/18/Tu154/134/Yk40 (Rossia)  Rwy 02/20 was listed as closed in 2005.
Length including overrun is 1650 m.  Services transport aircraft up to Il-76.
Navy base with An-72, An-26, An-12 and occasional Il-18/Il-22.  Also Gazpromavia's main base with An74's. One preserved Il14.  (Thanks to AviaMK)
Has handled most of Russia's Far East internal air routes since the 1960s. Now a major International Airport.  (AviaMK)  Parking for 95 jets.
Old airstrip south of Moscow; probably abandoned but may be of historical interest.  Indicated on JOG 1501 NN 37-1 and visible on satellite imagery.
Major transport base AN12/72/Tu154/Il76/IL86VKP. Chkalovsky received USSR's first Il-76K for cosmonaut training 23 July 1977.  May be confused with Kaliningrad/Chklalovsk or Omsk/Chkalovsk.
Very old airfield used as a display museum.  Small, narrow runway and of no significant wartime value. Has a Military Technical school with ramp which had an Il76 and two bombers (AviaMK).
An An-2 and Mil- helicopter reworks just outside Moscow (near Monino) Some DOSAAF aircraft are here for rework.  Obscured on Google Earth by clouds.
Terminal closed.  Ilyushin Il-76 and Yak-42 maintenance facility with many stored aircraft. (Thanks to AviaMK)

Services all types of aircraft.  Flight test center for military aircraft.  Named Ramenskoye by U.S.  The location Podmoskovnoye is found for international MiG-25 record-setting flights and translates to "Moscow area".
Utility and general aviation grass airstrip servicing An-2 and An-28 aircraft. (Thanks to AviaMK)  Cannot find it on satellite.
Helicopter operations base. (AviaMK)
The Tu-128 was originally fielded here in 1964.  Small airfield with utilitarian layout and small number of unpaved fighter revetments. [Savasleyka] [Murom] (US)
Kazan State Aviation Plant.  Tu-144, Tu-22M, and Il-62 production factory.  Large parking spaces on north side of airfield. Handles large airliners.  Very wide runway.
Old Kazan airfield; still has a few choppers and An-2s.  Google Earth showed it in the process of being torn up.
Handles medium-sized airliners.  Terminal area parks 20 aircraft.  The asphalt runway is built upon a dismantled 3500 m.
Very small airport; single tarmac with one building.
Minor airfield with utility tarmac and some hangars.  Appears to be an old airfield.
Services medium-sized airliners up to Tu-154 and Il-76.  Very large tarmac and a number of hangars and buildings.  Rwy 04/22 was closed as of late 2005.
Minor dirt airstrip with a gravel parking area.
Small airfield, probably part dirt and part asphalt.
Civilian airfield with small tarmac.
Services large airliners.  Parks up to 51 aircraft.
Services small airliners.  Military bomber training base had about 35 Tu134UBL's based in 95 (AviaMK).
Abandoned 1960s-era airfield; geometrics clearly visible but remnants almost completely gone.
Handles medium-sized airliners.
Appears to be an abandoned air base.
Small civilian airstrip with tarmac.  NDB beacon at airfield.
Utilitarian airfield An2/24/26/30 let410 base.  Large helicopter reworks plant. (AviaMK)

Large International airport.  Large civil ramp with 54 parking spaces.  Two runways, a close asphalt one and a remote concrete one, each 3650 m.  Military area in SE corner with An12/26 and Tu134UBL.  (AviaMK)

Large airfield on northeast side of Novosibirsk with tarmac space.  Handles Il-76 traffic, and Antonov factory and goverment experimental facilities are present (AviaMK). Directory lists length as 2864 m.

Civilian airfield serving medium-sized airliners, but large enough to be used for military purposes.  The 3200 m runway was built in 2000-2001.  Older 2750 m runway (05L/23R) is now a parallel taxiway.
Civilian airfield serving medium-sized airliners, but large enough to be used for military purposes.  Older 2750 m runway is now a parallel taxiway. [Kemerovo Southeast] (US)
Services small transport planes.
Airfield at northern tip of Lake Baikal handles small transport aircraft.  Well-maintained runway.
Abandoned airfield in forested area; a perimeter circles the airfield suggesting it may have had minor use in the 1940s and 1950s.
Airfield with several large buildings, probably capable of handling jet traffic.  Some revetments indicate that the base probably had a combat role in the 1950s or 1960s.
Rudimentary airfield with wide runway, servicing west central Kamchatka Peninsula.
Very short civilian airstrip.
Only airfield on Komandorskiye Ostrova (islands).  Satellite image quality is poor; confidence in geometrics is marginal.

Very old airfield (c. 1950s), nearly Russia's most extreme western point, with about 25 pads; appears to be in a severe state of decay.  The original 2000 m runway has been destroyed and shortened to 500 m to serve as a helicopter airstrip.
Russia's westernmost airfield, this airstrip is long abandoned and in severe decay.  It appears to house a small number of interceptor pads.
Handles medium-sized airliners; 9 parking spaces near terminal on south side.  Old airfield in extreme west Russia, probably for bomber aircraft, 30 large revetments along angular taxiway.
Appears to be a very old airfield (1950s-1960s) with spartan layout, unimproved pads, if any, and alert strip feeding directly onto runway threshold.  Now used by local residents for auto racing.

Kaliningrad's largest airfield, a significant military base with four separate complexes for bomber and fighter parking.  The Su-24 regiment is still stationed at the airfield.  Chkalovsk may be confused with "Chkalovsk" in Moscow and Omsk.
Small unimproved civilian airstrip used mainly for ultralight flying and paragliding.

This airfield is currently believed to be nonoperational; photographs on the Internet show open access and overgrown taxiways.  The airfield has a large mile-wide taxiway ring on west side feeding revetments.  Remote bomber or alert revetments for about 5 aircraft.  In state of decay.

Nuclear bomber base.  Medium sized interceptor airfield in Baltic region.  Its 4 Gv BAP and 63 BAP flew the Yak-28 starting in the 1960s.  At some point Tu-16 were based here.  It is home to 4 Gv MSHAP flying 29 Su-24 aircraft.  The 132 MShAD was based here, as was the 15 ODRAP.
Location doubtful.  Listed on GNC-3 1974 edition.
Probability a military forward deployment base.  Photographs show that this airfield is in decay and is nonoperational.
Runway length given as 3150 m on new DAFIF; was 2570x45 according to 1998-2000 Jeppesen and CAICA.  Terminal area parks 9 jets.
Civilian terminal and hangars parks 34 medium/large aircraft.  Lithuanian military Mil-8 base (AviaMK).
Appears to be an industrial airstrip; located in a large, newly cleared region.  Only 16 km from Belarus border.
Small 1950s-1960s era airfield with unpaved revetment complex hidden in forest to northwest.
1960s-era fighter or interceptor base.  Plowed under for farmland.  Geometrics plainly visible.
Appears to have been a forward deployment field.  Now plowed under into farmland.  A new major highway connecting Minsk to Moscow is just 1 km north of the former site.

Bomber base with long runway, large tarmac area, and 30 large revetments. Remote revetment area contains 5 bomber pads and probably 5 fighter pads.  The base was home to a bomber regiment since 1944.  It became the first nuclear bomber base around 1952 receiving the first Tu-16s.  402 TBAP is subordinate to 326 TBAD (Solcy).
Small mixed-use airfield.  Has 12 based Il-76 aircraft.  Remote revetment area with 8 pads.  Very active IL76 base with a Yakolev factory at the southeast corner.  (AviaMK)
Civilian airfield; small tarmac.  Many stored An-2s and a disused DOSAAF area.  (AviaMK)

Large hardened air base with pads for 19 bombers and 15 fighters in addition to a small amount of tarmac space.  Its units are 164 ORAP which flew the MiG-25 and Su-24 in the early 1990s, HQ VVS, 1046 Ts Pls flying 17 MiG-25, 14 Su-17C, and 13 Su-24 in the early 1990s [#4]; 47 Gv ORAP flying Su-24MR[#4] and MiG-25RB[#7]; and 98 Gv ORAP flying Yak-28R aircraft starting in the mid-1970s[#34].  Nuclear bomber base accoridng to NRDC.

column2: Anisovo Gorod, Anisovo Gorodishche (US), Shaykovo, Shaykovka, Gorodische, Chaikovka
column49: Large airfield with hangars and extensive alert area for fighters.  Appears overrun was being built to extend runway to 3000 m.  In 2000, Tu-160, Tu-95MS, and Tu-22M3 operated out of this base during training exercise.  Nuclear bomber base as per NRDC.
Accommodates small airliners.  Restricted area UU-R56 is located just southwest of airfield over part of Kaluga town.
Military base with Mil-8 helicopters.  Still operational.
Disused civil terminal military helicopter base. (AviaMK)
Was a military transport base until the mid-1990s.  Now a general aviation field.  (AviaMK)
Located 56 km NW of Ryazan.
Training center for nuclear bombers.  Large bomber base with room for 25 aircraft and tarmac space. A number of Tu-16, Tu-22, and M-4 are mothballed.  49 TBAP moved here 1985.
Small civilian airstrip.
MiL-8 and Mil-24 base of Russian Air Force. (AviaMK)
Civilian utilitarian airfield.
Probably a forward deployment airfield.
Services small airliners.
Runway is 94 m wide.
Appears to be a civilian/transport base.
May be a helicopter strip.
Small civilian airfield with paved runway and tarmac area.
Small airport with several hangars.  Services small prop transports.  The 2750 m runway was constructed in 2000-2001.
Services general aviation traffic.
Terminal area parks 37 aircraft.
Services small transport aircraft.
Appears to have an alert pad, thus an interceptor base.  Well maintained and long tarmac.
An active helicopter operations base.  About 30 revetments and very short runway.  Only 6 km from Kazakhstan border to south.
Ten large concrete parking pads and four small ones.  Several medium-sized aircraft parked here.
Handles medium-sized airliners.  Minor position discrepancy: Google Earth reports 54-46.5 69-11.0 while CAICA reports 54-45.2 69-11.2.
Handles large aircraft.  Width of 07/25 given as 80 m elsewhere.
Several large tarmacs, some large revetment areas.  It is possible that this was a bomber operations base at one time. May be confused with "Chkalovsk" in Moscow and Kaliningrad.
Fighter base with small fans of revetments.  Large central tarmac.

Formerly a major military airfield; the runway has been broken up.  A helicopter operations unit remains.  Disturbances in the terrain suggest that the original runway was at 54 43.7'N 83 05.8'E with a 1600 m length and 135 deg true heading.
Small civilian airstrip.  It appears the facility is old.  The rubble of the old airport terminal still remains.
Small civilian airstrip; paint markings visible.
Small civilian airfield.
Civilian airport with dirt runway.  Basic runway lights exist and there is a 20 x 15 m concrete parking pad.
Small civilian airstrip.
Civilian airport with dirt runway.
Civilian

Located 143 km N of Petropavlovsk in the center of Kamchatka.  Likely a forward staging base for bombers to reach California from Ukrainka, et al.  Very long runway.  Hardstands for 12 bombers, 3 fighters, and 2 service areas, tarmac area.

Pads in forested area for about 30 transport aircraft and a small number of fighters.  It was the home of an ORAP unit that flew Yak-28R aircraft starting in the 1970s[#34].

Military air base which is still active.  Medium-sized airfield with revetments and aircraft bunkers.  Belarus Air Force stations Su-24 aircraft here, which participated in a joint defense exercise with its sister base Siverskiy in Leningradskaya.
Medium-sized airfield has sprawling taxiways with over 40 revetments.  Headquarters 1st Bomber Division (1 BAD), tenant 497 BAP responsible to this division.

Large sprawling airfield.  Two remote revetment areas, and 30 bomber pads with about 15 fighter pads.  Was active as a bomber base in 2000.  Located near large early warning radar (Volga Facility).  203 TBAP subordinate to 22 TBAD (Bobruysk).  Base has been in major use since November 7, 1951 when it received 45th TBAD or BAD and 203rd TBAP and became one of the prime strategic bomber base of the early 1950s.  It conducted numerous Tu-16A sorties to the high arctic starting in the mid 1950s.  It also deployed a Tu-16 to Tiksi and onward to ice station SP-6 for field trials in 1958.  61 IAP either is in Kokaydy or moved there.
Former helicopter base on northeast side of Minsk; still operational.  Many Mi-2 and some An-2 stored.  Museum with MiG-25, MiG-27U, Su-17, and a few helicopters. (AviaMK).
Helicopter base.  It is shown as having MiL-6 (now doubtful) and MiL-8/9 (possible) but nothing else (AviaMK).

Handles small airliners; terminal area has 54 major parking spaces.  Has the Aviation Repair Plant 407, which handles rework of Tupolev Tu-134/Yak-40/Yak-42, handling both civil and military versions of the 134. (AviaMK)
This position is estimated due to complete destruction of the airfield.  Minsk Chizovka is now the site of the Institute for the Belarus Air Force.

Large base with 16 large, hardened revetments in remote taxiway loop.  It hosted 52 Gv TBAP bomber regiment as early as 1951 or 1952.  Was active as a bomber base in 2000, and participated in exercises with Russia in 2005.  Handles medium-sized airliners.  The 200 TBAP is subordinate to 22 TBAD (Bobruysk).
Large civilian airport.  Terminal area parks 26 aircraft; cargo apron to southeast.  Rwy 13/31 has overrun of 400 m at either end.
Appears to be an abandoned airfield long plowed under.  Geometric uncertain.  Shown on JNC-10.

Large bomber base.  Capacity for 42 large bombers in individual revetments. Also has about 10 revetments in separate alert interceptor area.  Headquarters 22nd Heavy Bomber Division (22 TBAD).  Reportedly TBAPs were closed 1994.
Handles medium-sized airliners.

Located about 42 km south of Mogilev (Mahiljow), this is a large bomber base.  Revetments on southwest side for 16 large bombers, with space for about 15 fighters on northeast side.  Received Tu-16 in 1955. [Byhau]
Small base, no hardened areas and some narrow tarmac space.
Unusual large ring taxiway a mile in diameter, feeding numerous revetments (18 large aircraft on south side, 27 small aircraft on north side).  Nuclear bomber base according to NRDC.
1960s-era bomber base.  Completed plowed under, geometrics barely show on satellite.

This is an old military airfield that has been destroyed and is no longer in service.  A public road cuts through the former airfield and there is an industrial park on the old ramps.  This airfield appeared as late as 1993 on Jeppesen charts, suggesting it may have been Bryansk's old civilian airfield.

Services medium-sized airliners.  Utilitarian layout.  This did not appear on a 1993 Jeppesen chart, and runways look new, so it may be the new civilian airfield.  Accomodates 6 jets, 2 cargo planes, and 32 general aviation planes.

This airfield was abandoned during the 1990s.  It was a large facility with numerous revetments, and is now in a state of decay.
Military training airfield until around 1990.  The airfield is abandoned and is now in a state of decay.

Decaying WWII German airfield.  The Tatsinskaya Airfield was the main airfield used by the German Wehrmacht during the Battle of Stalingrad to supply the encircled 6th Army from outside [WIKI].  From Tatsinskaya, a Ju 52 plane would take approx. 1 hour to reach Stalingrad, from where it would return after a 3 hour turnaround, theoretically making it possible to complete a mission in six hours; Tatsinskaya served as the main base for the Ju 52 transport planes, while Morozovskaya was mainly used by the He 111 bombers, which were converted to transport plane [WIKI].  The airfield was under threat of being taken by the Soviet Red Army but Hermann Gring forbade its evacuation, despite request from Major General Fiebig, who was in charge of the air supply for Stalingrad [WIKI]. On 23 December Gring give permission to evacuate, but it was too late; Tatsinskaya was overrun a day later, with the German Luftwaffe losing almost 70 of the 180 Ju 52s stationed there and all ground equipment [WIKI]. The fall of the airfield, along with the one at Morozovskaya being threatened, brought supplies to the 6th Army to a halt until the 26th [WIKI].  Also briefly retaken by the Germans on the 28th, Tatsinskaya fell back into Soviet hands by 31 December [WIKI].  After the fall of Tatsinskaya, the Ju 52 from there were relocated to Salsk, while the He 111 went to Novocherkassk, increasing the distance to travel considerably.Part of the runway is 80 m wide, suggesting that alert aircraft were parked along the main runway itself.

The Pitomnik airfield (Russian: ????????, lit. plant nursery) was an airfield in Russia, the primary of the seven airfields used by the German Wehrmacht during the Battle of Stalingrad within the city [WIKI].  Pitomnik was captured by the German 6th Army when it linked up there with the 4th Panzer Army on 3 September 1942 [WIKI].  The airfield at Pitomnik was one of seven airfields within the Stalingrad pocket and the only one properly equipped to handle large amounts of traffic. It was equipped with lights for night operation [WIKI].  As of 2009, the location of the Pitomnik Airfield is used as farmland [WIKI].
