Airfield indicated on GNC-13 but location doubtful due to poor satellite imagery.  Airfield probably abandoned decades ago.
Major highway strip with turnouts.  Unable to see many details due to poor satellite imagery.
Highway strip; two reveted areas, one parallel strip.
Appears to be an abandoned 1950s-era airfield.  Parallel taxiway.  Only about 100 km from Chinese border, so probably served as a front-line defense for Alma Ata against Urumqi-region attacks.

Medium-sized air base near Mikhailovka.  Runway reportedly upgraded 1987.  Major nuclear bomber base (sister of Khorol).  Long runway and curved taxiways with large revetments.  Runway width is 60 m but only 40 m is usable.  APIB under 1st Air Army Far East.
Small agricultural or town airstrip.  No buildings onsite.
Military airfield listed on 1980 JNC chart.  Unable to precisely locate on satellite imagery due to snow cover, but traces of a dirt airstrip visible on declassified imagery from 1967.
Airfield southwest of Vladivostok had tarmacs and taxiways and may have been a 1940s or 1950s air base.  Demolished but geometrics are still visible.
Abandoned military airfield.  Covered by snow in Google Earth imagery.
Appears to be a large abandoned military base, probably a fighter base from the 1950s or 1960s.
Abandoned military airfield in severe disrepair.  Runway width is 60 m but only 35 m is reinforced and marked.

Vladivostok's international airport.  Handles all aircraft sizes; 22 parking spots.  Fighter revetments appear to be decaying, but a remote revetment area with 11 concrete pads exists.  Rwy 07R/25L closed.
Isolated base 20 miles east of Vladivostok appears to be a forward operating location with about 15 hardened revetments and some tarmac space.  150 m runway overrun each side.
Military combat base.  Unknown status.  Name Novorossiya is as given on 1980 JNC chart.
Military combat base.  Original runway length appears to have been 970 m with possible planned extension to 1800 m.  Contains a few helicopters and some utility planes.

Medium air base 37 km NE of Nakhodka.  Sprawling base with remote revetment area and loop revetment, harboring a total of 30 large spaces and about 10 smaller ones.  No tarmac space.  During WWII Yak-3s were based here.
Minor civilian airfield with paved runway.
Appears to be an abandoned construction project for a combat fighter base covering southeastern Primorski Kray.  Listed on 1980 JNC chart as "abandoned".
Small civilian airfield located on Ostrov Kunashir.  One small parking apron.  This is the closest airfield to Japan, at a distance of only 50 km.  Listed as Sernovodsk on US DoD GNC-6 (1977).
Civilian airport; terminal area parks 6 medium/large aircraft and 31 smaller planes.  Joint use airfield (DAFIF).

Former military airfield with about 30 revetments along angular system of taxiways.  Neglected appearance and substandard runway length indicates this is 1950s-1960s era.  May be a civilian airfield now.  Not on ONC or JNC charts.
Military combat airfield with numerous aircraft shelters.  Appears to be starting to decay.
This was a military base that was home to 143 BAP flying Yak-28 Brewer bombers[#34].
Pasture now occupies the site of a 1950s-1960s era airfield.  Runway is demolished.  Some revetments still stand and it may serve as a helicopter facility.
Handles medium-sized airliner traffic. Parking for 4 jets and dozens of smaller aircraft.
Joint civil-military airfield.  Different source gave ICAO of UTNN.
Decaying military airfield.
Appears runway may have originally been 4000 m and was broken up into smaller portions.
Civilian tarmac servicing medium-sized airliners.  Some fighter revetments.  ((73rd Air Army Central Asia))
Almost no trace remains of this former airfield.  It appears to have had a 2 km runway.  Some Li-2s are based here, suggesting that a dirt airstrip is still being used.
Numerous revetments.  Services medium-sized airliners.
Possible bomber airfield; double taxiways with considerable tarmac space and no revetments.  Being used as a storage area for MiG-23s[18].
Probably a civilian airfield.
Possible civilian/military.
Civilian airfield (DAFIF).  Large ramp.
Barely visible.
Probably a former utilitarian airfield.
Small civilian airfield with packed gravel runway.
Minor civil airstrip.
Location doubtful.  Appears to be an old abandoned dirt airstrip.
This base has a few long taxiways with a few revetments.
Airfield looks somewhat abandoned.  Is the closest airfield to Turkey along the Black Sea coast, except for Batumi.
Civilian airport servicing small airliners (Tu-134, etc).
Now an agricultural field, the remains of an old airfield can be seen on satellite imagery.
Services large airliners; terminal area parks 22 medium/large aircraft and 28 small aircraft.
Airfield is abandoned or in poor condition.  Located only 3 km southwest of Tbilisi Lochini civilian airport.
Minor military airfield 28 km south of Tbilisi with small tarmac space.
This appears to be the western side of Stepanavan/Kalilino.
Small civilian airstrip.
Located 5 miles east of Tbilisi airport, this is a military base with numerous revetments.  Its status is unknown, though satellite indicates some overgrowth.  Military (DAFIF).
Small civilian airfield.
Added thanks to DAFIF.
Civil Terminals northwest and east; large IL76 base air base with some revetments on west and southwest; civil Il-76 storage on northeast ramp (AviaMK).  Well-maintained asphalt runway.
Large forward-deployment attack airfield.  About 50 revetments with hardened shelters along several angular taxiways.  Georgia's most easterly military airfield.
Utilitarian civilian airstrip.
Very small civilian airport.
Services medium-sized airliners. Runway 09R/27L closed.
Services large airliners.  24-hour operations.
Civilian airfield.
Civilian airfield (DAFIF).
Civilian airfield.

column48: 136 APIB (Su-17,1988) under 49th Air Army (Turkmenistan).  419th Fighter Regiment (32 Su-27).
column49: Large fighter base 34 km NE of Tashkent.  Various revetments along taxiways.  (49th Air Army Turkmenistan)
Factory airfield (AviaMK).
Major international airport with 90 mixed parking spaces and services up to Boeing 747s. Ilyushin reworks facility with many stored aircraft.  (AviaMK)
Small civilian airfield.
Appears to be a minor civilian airfield with a long runway length due to high elevation.

column48: Mixed.  121 ShAE (5 Su-25, mid 1990s) (2 L-39, mid 1990s).
column49: Services medium-sized airliners.  Only 10 km from Turkish border.  Terminal area parks 7 aircraft.   S-300 antiaircraft missile systems are based here.  On 02 Sep 1958 a U.S. Air Force C-130 ELINT plane was shot down here, killing 17.  Was UGEL.
Added thanks to DAFIF entry.
Handles medium-sized airliners; parks 14 aircraft at circular terminal and 12 at nearby apron.  Large civilian airport (AviaMK).  Listed as UGEE by 1998-2000 Jeppesen and CAICA.
Small airliners.  In 1990s was helicopter base of 15 SAP, with six Mi-24Ks, seven Mi-24Ps (including "42" outlinned in white) and two Mi-24Rs, seven Mi-17s and Mi-8MTKs, and two Mi-2s.
Large military base probably serving as interceptor and attack airfield.  No evidence of it being active.

Significant military facility with 28 bomber pads (presumably for Tu-16 and Tu-22 type aircraft) and two dozen attack revetments.  The runway length does not suggest an intercontinental role.  Civilian terminal on west side parks 4 planes.  In June 1992 the Azerbaijani military took this base by force from Russia, gaining eleven (western sources say 16) Su-24MRs, 20 MiG-25RBs, and three Il-76 transports.  Now is used as a transport base.
Definite civilian airfield; utilitarian layout.
Poorly maintained airstrip; definitely civilian.  On 02 Apr 1992 a pilot defected to Azerbaijan with a Su-25 from Sital-Chay and landed it here.
Primary Azerbaijani Air Force base, with considerable number of fighter and trainer aircraft.
Aging military base with attack role; does not appear to be a large facility.  Numerous revetments.  Appears to be nonoperational.

Large military base; only taxiways and tarmac space; no revetments.  On 08 Apr 1992 Senior Lt. Vagif Kurbanov hijacked a Su-25 from Sital-Chay and flew it to Yevlakh, Azerbaijan, giving the country its first fixed-wing fighter.
Small base 35 km NW of Baku, with tarmac area and a few revetments.   PVO regiment equipped with MiG-25PDs.
Military base with numerous attack revetments.  Located along shore of Caspian Sea 46 km SW of Baku.
Major civilian airport.  International terminal and parking for up to 54 aircraft.

Large facility but use is unclear.  No revetments.  An old airfield pattern exists west of the runway.  This is the easternmost airfield in the Baku region.  Large facility, Il76 An12 based/stored (thanks to AviaMK).
Shown on GNC-4 but not seen on satellite.
Shown on GNC-4 but not seen on satellite.
Accommodates medium-size airliners.  Joint use airport; 24-hour operations (DAFIF).
Appears to be a forward deployment base.  Wide runway with limited parking areas.  Barracks to southeast.
Abandoned utilitarian airfield; faint impression of reveted pads.
Civilian airfield.  Runway is built in several sections of varying width and age, and one portion appears to be closed.  Usable length may be only about 1500 m.
Listed as a military airfield by DAFIF.
Airstrip with turnouts and parking areas built on a 4-lane highway.  The turnouts are now decaying and occupied by buildings, so the role of the airfield as a combat strip is probably obsolete.
Accommodates medium-sized airliners.  Jeppesen 1998 had length of 2620 m; using DAFIF 3185 m.
Civilian airfield.
Minor civilian airfield with very long runway and minor tarmac space.  No noteworthy structures.
Small military airstrip (DAFIF).
Accommodates up to medium-sized airliners.
Probably a training base or forward deployment airfield.
Aircraft is equipped to service medium-sized airliners as well as large military aircraft.  Numerous revetments.
May be abandoned; status is unknown.
Joint use airport.  Avia.ru gives length of 2900 m.
Services up to medium-sized airliners; 22 parking spaces near terminal.  Only 2 km from border to west.
Handles small transport aircraft.  Only 4 km from border to west.
Presence of barracks or apartments near airfield suggests a military garrison, though airfield may be civilian.  Serves the resort town of Jermuk.
Only 9 km from Turkish border.  Joint use airfield (DAFIF).
Appears to be civilian
Probably civilian.
Appears to be civilian.  Only 1 km from Azerbaijani border.  A 125 x 60 m pad exists for possible transport and cargo activity.
Major military facility that is abandoned or unused.  The runway ends have peculiar butterfly parking spaces, suggesting a PVO interceptor role during the 1950s.
Appears to be a decaying military facility.
Appears to be an aging forward deployment airfield; numerous revetments along curved taxiway 600 m from main runway, plus tarmac.
Attack airfield; numerous revetments, with housing and barracks area.  Probably was very active; but substandard runway length suggests this was in the 1950s and 1960s.
Small civilian airstrip.
Military base with numerous revetments.
Medium base 2 miles south of Nebitdag (formerly Nebit-Dag).  Contains 5 large revetments at corner of airfield, and numerous small ones along parallel taxiway.
Shown on GNC-4 but does not exist on satellite.
Services medium-sized airliners.  Mixed use civil/military airfield; 24-hour operations (DAFIF, other sources).
Civilian airfield; 24-hour operations.
Old substandard military airfield with about 40 revetments.  Length given as 1900 elsewhere (maybe from image measurement).
Appears to be a 1950s-1960s  military airfield; taxiways are substandard.
Services large airliners; 24-hour operations.  Terminal area parks 16 medium/large planes and 42 small planes.
Small dirt airstrip.
Shown on GNC-4 but cannot be found on satellite.
Very short but well-serviced civilian airstrip.
Appears to be a former military airfield.
Standard fighter base.  (49th Air Army, Turkmenistan)
Appears to be a civilian airfield as runway is thin.  It is possible this airstrip may have been turned into a residential street.

column2: Ashkabad Northwest (US), Ak-tepe, Bezmain (US), Ashkabad Bezmain (US), Ashgabat Bezmain
column49: Small fighter base with reveted areas.  MiG-23M piloted by V. Shkinder shot down Iranian CH-47C 7/21/78.  U.S. Air Force presence, either at this base or at Ashkabad/Civil.

column2: K2, Karshi Khanabad, Camp Stronghold Freedom (US), Kandabad (erroneous spelling)
column49: Home to 87 ORAP flying Yak-28Rs in the mid 1970s[#34].  It acquired Su-24MR in the 1980s.  In the early 1980s this was a Tu-16 base (alongside Mary and Semipalitinsk) for Afghanistan bombing operations.  Now operated by Uzbekistan Air Force.  The U.S. Air Force used the facility from October 2001 to July 2005 as the central base for Afghanistan operations; the lease was terminated due to increasing tensions between the U.S. and Uzbekistan.
Accommodates medium-sized airliners.  Sources vary between 364 m (DoD) and 373 m (avia.ru).
Appears to be a civilian airfield, though a parallel taxiway raises some doubt.  Only 14 km from Tadzhikistan border, to east.
Large civilian airport, regularly servicing medium jetliners.  Parks 63 aircraft.
Joint use airport (DAFIF).
Small civilian utilitarian airfield.  Exact location and geometrics uncertain due to poor satellite imagery.
One of highest airfields in former Soviet Union.  (Added thanks to DAFIF)

Major military airfield that appears to have been abandoned in the 1980s or 1990s and has been quarried for concrete and partially destroyed.  It is 13 km from the Iranian border.  A 2000 JNC chart reported "not usable".
Civilian airfield; 47 parking spaces and a ramp southwestof terminal area for 13 helicopters.  24-hour operations (DAFIF).
Abandoned military facility that has been partially dismantled.  An industrial building exists on the northwest end of the former runway.
Abandoned 1950s-era airfield on southeastern side of Tedzhen; appears to have been long demolished.  Position and dimensions approximate.
According to <http://www.internetelite.ru/cosmopark/tu22t2.html>, in December 1987-January 1988 two squadrons of 185 Gv TBAP were transferred from Poltava (Ukraine) to Maryi.  Combat Training Center.
Handles small airliner traffic.
Abandoned 1950s-era field; no longer exists.
Small utilitarian airfield.  U.S. Air Force presence.
GNC-4 shows an airfield here, but none is found on imagery.
Confidence in this location is low but appears there is a faint outline of an airstrip within crop patterns.  Obviously this is an old military airfield that was plowed over decades ago.

column48: 115 Gv APIB (Su-17) (MiG-29), under 49th Air Army (Turkmenistan); this location is not confirmed.
column49: Small fighter base 150 km SW of Dushanbe.  This was the USSR's closest base to the Afghanistan border.  The location of 115 Gv APIB is suspected to be here, but is not confirmed.
Services medium-sized airliners; main terminal has 7 medium/large parking spaces and 31 small spaces.
Handles small transport aircraft.
Appears to be an abandoned civilian airfield
Abandoned airfield that is now in a severe state of decay.  The runway is unusable.
Military airfield (DAFIF).
(Added thanks to DAFIF)
Airstrip in very mountainous region, on riverbank on Afghanistan border.  May be one of the most dangerous approaches in the USSR.
Civilian airfield (DAFIF).

Former Soviet Union's southernmost airfield.  Appears to be civilian, with utilitarian layout, but some old taxiways suggest a possible former light-duty forward deployment attack role.  Military according to DAFIF.
Airfield is out of service.

In 1965 had MiG-17F, MiG-21, Yak-12, MiG-15UTI aircraft, but by the 1970s the base had upgraded to MiG-23 aircraft.  During the early 1990s it was run by the 773 IAP operating MiG-29, MiG-23UM, and An-2 aircraft.  It was used as a stopover for a departing MiG-29 regiment in 1994.  Airfield is out of service and all Russian buildings have been demolished.  Access is restricted.

In 1965 the airfield had MiG-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft, plus an Il-28 target towing regiment.  The fighter regiment upgraded to the MiG-21 in the 1970s, and a Mi-24 helicopter regiment operated at the airfield.  The housing areas were destroyed around 2000.  An industrial park is planned at this airfield and improvements to the airfield have been made.
A MiG-23 regiment left in March 1993.  Runway length originally 2400 m.  Pavement in poor condition.

In 1965 the airfield had MiG-19, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft, but was upgraded to the MiG-21 in the 1970s.  By the 1990s it was home to the 33 IAP operating MiG-23 and MiG-29 aircraft.  The last Russian regiment, flying MiG-29 aircraft, departed in 1994.  The runway appears to have been used for drag racing.
The 368 ShAP (Su-25) left for Russia in June 1993.  The airfield is operational due to private investment.
Supposedly this base was on the east side of the town of Prenzlau; no trace remains.  The 487 OVP flew here around 1990 using Mi-8 and Mi-24 aircraft.
In 1965 the base had Il-28, MiG-17, Mi-1, and Yak-12, plus an Il-28 and Li-2 target towing regiment.  By the 1970s it had only a Yak-28 regiment and a Mi-24 helicopter regiment.
Home to a Russian Mi-24 helicopter fleet, which returned home around 1994.  Decaying combat base; runway in poor condition.

In 1965, Zerbst had MiG-17, MiG-19, MiG-21, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft, and possibly Su-9 or Su-11 aircraft.  The regiment was operating only the MiG-21 in the 1970s.  In the early 1990s it was operated by the 35 IAP flying MiG-29, MiG-23UM, and An-2.  Refugees were housed here in the early 1990s.  The airfield was used by NATO in 2002.
In 1965 the airfield had MiG-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft.  The base upgraded to the MiG-27 by the mid-1970s.
In 1965 the airfield was home to MiG-17, Su-7, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI.  Only the Su-7 was left in the 1970s.  The airfield pavement is in poor condition and only 2080 m are usable.

Major combat air base with numerous reveted areas.  In 1965 it was home to Li-2, An-2, Il-14, Mi-4, Il-18, An-10, and Tu-104 jet.  By the mid-1970s it was operating only the An-2 and An-12.  It was at one time examined for a Berlin airport expansion plan.
In 1965 the base had Il-28, Yak-28, and Yak-12 aircraft.  It was operating only the Su-17 by the 1970s.  Around 1990 the 487 OVP operated here flying Mi-8 and Mi-24 helicopters.  Abandoned.

In 1965 the base had Il-28, Yak-28, and Yak-12.  It was operating only the Yak-28 by the 1970s.  Brand was a MiG-27 base.  In 1993 it was a refugee center.  In the mid-1990s it was purchased by CargoLifter and used as an airship base, an endeavor that went bankrupt in 2002.  It is now the site of My Tropical Islands resort.

In 1965 the airfield had MiG-17, MiG-21, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI, but these were replaced with MiG-21 in the mid-1970s.  The 487 OVP operated here in the 1990s flying Mi-8 and Mi-24.  The last Russian regiment departed in April 1994.
Runway is 2200 m long but only 1500 m is marked for use, avoiding the east end.  A smaller embedded 1200 x 30 m runway is marked for use on the west end.
In 1965 the base had Il-28, Yak-28, and Yak-12.  It was operating only the Su-7 by the 1970s.  The 787 IAP (flying MiG-23UM and MiG-29 aircraft) returned to Russia in May 1993.
Runway is marked down to 2712 x 45 m.
It was home to an An-12 regiment in 1965.  It was flying An-14 aircraft in the 1970s.  Airfield is in the process of being destroyed and quarried.
In 1965 it was a helicopter base with Mi-6 and Mi-4 helicopters.  It had An-26 aircraft in the mid-1970s.

Cochstedt is an airfield in excellent condition and has received a coat of asphalt on top of the original Soviet concrete construction; also some of the Warsaw Pact runway marks appear to be gone, such as the centerpoint circle.  Only 45 m of width is marked off for use.  Runway length is 3100 m counting the overrun.

In 1965 Kothen had MiG-21, MiG-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft.  By the 1970s it was operating only the MiG-21.  In the early 1990s it was operated by the 73 Gv IAP flying MiG-29 and MiG-23UM.  The airfield was used for off-road truck testing in the mid-1990s.  The airfield is now being destroyed.

In 1965 Merseburg had MiG-17, MiG-21, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft.  It upgraded to the MiG-23MS in the 1970s.  By the 1990s it was home to 85 Gv IAP flying MiG-29, MiG-23UM, and An-2 aircraft.  The airfield has been transformed into a minor general aviation airfield and has a museum.  Only a 1200 x 30 m subset of the runway is available.
The 357 ShAP (Su-25 and L-39) returned to Russia in spring 1992.  Only a small 1420 x 30 m subsection of the runway is in use now.

Juterbog is a former East German military airfield.  In 1965 it had MiG-21, MiG-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft. It had upgraded to the MiG-23MS in the 1970s.  The Russian 833 IAP (26 MiG-23MLD and 8 MiG-23UB, plus An-2 aircraft) returned to Russia in May 1992.  It has been destroyed and quarried, with 1300 m of runway remaining.

In 1965 the base had MiG-21, MiG-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI aircraft.  It was operating only MiG-21 aircraft in the 1970s.  By the 1990s the 31 Gv IAP was operating here with MiG-29 and MiG-23UM, and returned to Russia in June 1993.  Falkenberg is decaying and the runway has been reduced to a 1200 x 30 subset of the original 3000 m runway.  Some of the taxiways have been torn up.

In 1965 the base had MiG-17, Su-7 or Su-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI.  It was operating only the Yak-28 by the 1970s.  A MiG-23 regiment returned to Russia in March 1993.  Only a 1200 x 30 m subset of the original runway is in use.

In 1965 the base had MiG-17, Su-7 or Su-17, Yak-12, and MiG-15UTI.  It was operating only the Yak-28 in the 1970s.  The original runway has been reduced to a 1425 x 45 m subset of the original 2400 m runway.
Only a 1570 x 40 m subset of the original runway is marked for use.
Runway is 80 m wide but only 50 m is usable.

In 1965 it was home to Il-28, Il-14, Mi-1, and Yak-12 aircraft.  By the 1970s it had only the An-12.  The 11 RAP (Su-24MR) returned to Russia in June 1993.  Old East German military airfield in decaying condition.
Old East German military airfield.

Old East German military airfield.  In 1965 it had a large MiG-17 regiment plus Yak-12 and MiG-15UTI planes.  It was operating only the MiG-21 in the 1970s and had a reconnaissance regiment flying the MiG-21R.  By the 1990s it was operated by the 968 IAP flying MiG-29 and MiG-23UM, plus an An-2.  Only a 1670 x 45 m subset of the runway is now marked for use.
Very large airfield facility.

The 22nd Air Base (Polish: 22. baza lotnicza) is a Polish Air Force base, located near Malbork. It was officially constituted on 1 January 2001, replacing the disbanded 41st Fighter Aviation Regiment. The main unit based there is the 41st Air Tactical Squadron flying MiG-29 fighters.  (ALL TEXT FROM WIKIPEDIA)

Szczecin-Goleniw "Solidarno??" Airport (Polish: Port Lotniczy Szczecin-Goleniw im. NSZZ "Solidarno??") is the main domestic and international airport serving the city of Szczecin in Poland and is located 45 km northeast of the city, near the town of Goleniw. About 1.6 million residents live within its catchment. [VERBATIM FROM WIKIPEDIA]
Polish Air Force fighter base that has fallen into neglect.  It is not believed to be operational.
Polish Air Force fighter base.
Active Polish Air Force base still in good condition.
Military base in unknown condition.

Bydgoszcz Ignacy Jan Paderewski Airport (Polish: port lotniczy im. ignacego jana paderewskiego bydgoszcz-szwederowo) is a Polish regional airport in the city of Bydgoszcz, Poland. It lies only 3 km (1.9 miles) from the city center. It is the tenth airport in Poland in terms of passenger traffic. Currently the airport features one passenger terminal and one runway with dimmensions 2500 x 60 m. Plans for development in 2007-2013 include extending the runway and building a cargo terminal. [WIKIPEDIA]  The runway width is 80 m but only 60 m is marked for use.  The base originally had a military purpose and numerous hardened revetments exist around the airfield.
Location suspected but uncertain.
Location suspected but uncertain.

Former military airfield along the western frontier of Poland.  Zielona Gra-Babimost Airport is the 10th busiest in Poland. It has recently been taken over from the Polish Army by the regional authorities.
Pozna?-?awica Airport , built in 1913, is one of the oldest airports in Poland. It is located 7 km west of the Pozna? city centre.

The 33rd Air Base (Polish: 33. baza lotnicza) is a Polish Air Force base, located near Powidz. It was officially constituted on 1 January 2000 as the 21st airbase, replacing the disbanded 7th Bomber-Reconnaissance Aviation Regiment, then redesignated to its current name on January 1, 2001.  The base has one of the longest runways in Poland.  A smaller taxiway serves as a 2750 m runway.
Major airfield serving as the western front-line defense for Warsaw.

Warsaw Frederic Chopin Airport (Polish: Port Lotniczy im. Fryderyka Chopina) is an international airport located in the Ok?cie district of Warsaw, Poland. Formerly Ok?cie International Airport, it is named after the famous Polish composer and former Warsaw resident, Frdric Chopin. It is Poland's busiest airport, handling more than 50% of the country's air passenger traffic.

The 23rd Air Base (Polish: 23 baza lotnicza) is a Polish Air Force base, located 6 km east of Mi?sk Mazowiecki. It was officially constituted on 1 January 2001, replacing the disbanded 1st Aviation Regiment "Warszawa". The main unit based there is the 1st Air Tactical Squadron flying MiG-29 fighters.
Airfield abandoned and destroyed probably in the 1970s or 1980s.  Last listed on a 1970s GNC chart.
This is the southwesternmost major airfield in Poland and is close to Osla.
Located in the southwestern corner of Poland.
Serves the city of Wroclaw.
On 1 September 2007 two planes crashed at the Radom Air Show in front of about thirty thousand spectators.
Believed to be decommissioned.

Katowice International Airport is an international airport located in Pyrzowice.  The airport features two passenger terminals A and B (completed in 2007) and a cargo terminal. Its concrete runway is 2,799 m long and 59 m wide and can accommodate any Boeing 747 or Boeing 777. Heavy transports such as An-124 or An-225 are sometimes seen here.
Karlovy Vary is now an international airport.  It is only about 50 km from the German border.
This military airfield is the second northernwesternmost airfield in the Czech Republic.

Hrad?any Airport (Letit? Ralsko) is a former military airport in area of town Ralsko in Liberec Region, northern part of the Czech Republic. Built toward the end of World War II for Luftwaffe it was expanded after the war. In 1968 Soviet Army took control and set up large air base here. After the Soviets left in 1991 the airport was abandoned and devastated.
Prague-Ruzyn? is the biggest airport in the Czech Republic and with 11.6 million passengers in 2006
This seems to be primarily an airport for utilitarian use, not a combat airfield.
Front line Czech airfield with no taxiways or support buildings.  Served as a dispersal base.
Front line Czech dispersal airfield, with one parallel taxiways and no significant infrastructure.
Brno-Tu?any Airport is an airport near Brno, Czech Republic. In 2006, 393 686 passengers went through Brno-Tu?any passenger terminal.
Listed on 1974 GNC; unable to locate.
Dispersal airfield.
Strategic bomber airfield.  As of February 2004 satellite showed no aircraft at this base.
Minor dispersal airfield with revetments containing about 30 An-2 aircraft as of October 2005.

This airfield is about 30 km east of the historic Mt Paekdu area.  The airfield has a highly developed infrastructure.  Satellite imagery as of 2009 did not show any aircraft of note, but image quality was poor.
Unpaved utilitarian airstrip.  May have had concrete at one time that was reclaimed.
Taxiway system leads into hardened shelters in mountains nearby.  Satellite image quality is not good enough to resolve individual aircraft.
Major military airfield with sprawling taxiway arrangement and revetments.  Serves primary Harbin H-5 (Il-28 Beagle), about 38 unique examples identified on August 2003 - January 2004.
Major military airfield.  Satellite picture quality is not good, however.

This is a former Soviet airbase that housed a MiG-21 regiment.
